## helper function
visual <- function(dataset, alpha, beta){
  x <- seq(0,1,by=0.001)
  fitted_val <- dbeta(x, shape1=alpha, shape2=beta)
  fitted_data <- data.frame(x, fitted_val)
  g <- ggplot(dataset, aes(x=prop_s)) +
    geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), colour="black", fill="white")+
    geom_density(alpha=.2, colour="palevioletred1",fill="palevioletred1")+
    geom_point(data = fitted_data, aes(x = x, y = fitted_val), colour = "cornflowerblue", size=0.1, show.legend = TRUE)+
    # labs(title = "Patient - m=100, p1=0.03, p2=0.01")+
    theme_bw()
  return(g)
}

Hypothesis test

\[ H_0: s \ \ \text{follows beta distribution} \\ H_0: s \ \ \text{doesn't follow beta distribution} \]

Under the null hypothesis, beta CDF (s) should follow unif(0,1), and then T = -2log(beta CDF (s)) should follow \(Chi^2_2\) distribution.

likelihood ratio test

likelihood_test <- function(data){
  n <- length(data)
  eff_n <- sum(!is.na(data)) # the number of non-na elements
  print(paste("The number of non-na elements is",eff_n)) 
  
  par <- ebeta(data, method = "mle") # the warning may come from the fact that several values = 1
  alpha_star <- as.numeric(par$parameters[1])
  beta_star <- as.numeric(par$parameters[2])
  print(paste("The mle estimator for alpha = ", alpha_star, "beta =", beta_star)) 
  
  # Bootstrap sampling to construct the empirical distribution
  M <- 1000  # the number of bootstrap
  alpha_emp <- numeric(M)
  beta_emp <- numeric(M)
  T_emp <- numeric(M)

  set.seed(156)
  for (i in 1:M) {
    boot_s <- rbeta(n, shape1 = alpha_star, shape2 = beta_star)
    par_emp <- ebeta(boot_s, method = "mle") 
    alpha_emp[i] <- as.numeric(par_emp$parameters[1])
    beta_emp[i] <- as.numeric(par_emp$parameters[2]) 
    cdf <- numeric(n)
    for (j in 1:n) {
      s <- boot_s[j]
      cdf[j] <- -2*log(pbeta(s, shape1 = alpha_emp[i], shape2 = beta_emp[i]))
    }
    T_emp[i] <- sum(cdf)/n
  }

  # histogram(alpha_emp)
  # histogram(beta_emp)
  # mean(alpha_emp)
  # mean(beta_emp)
  h <- histogram(T_emp)
  print(h)

  # the observed statistics
    cdf_obs <- numeric(n)
  for (i in 1:n){
    s <- data[i]
    cdf_obs[i] <- -2*log(pbeta(s, shape1 = alpha_star, shape2 = beta_star))
  }
  T_obs <- sum(cdf_obs)/n
  print(paste("The observed statistics is", T_obs)) 

  # calculating p-value
  d <- abs(T_obs - mean(T_emp))
  p_val <- (sum(T_emp<=mean(T_emp)-d) + sum(T_emp>=mean(T_emp)+d) )/ M
  print(paste("The p-value is", p_val)) 
  return(c(alpha_star, beta_star, p_val))
}

Conclusion

According to the results above likelihood ratio test, we believe that under Patient algorithm, we don’t have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis, which is the distribution of ratio \(s\) follows a beta distribution; for Greedy algorithm, those p-values are smaller than \(0.05\), therefore, we conclude that the distribution of ratio \(s\) doesn’t follow a beta distribution.
